"@Xena":/dis/the-time-wasting-thread/post/558f5be5636872710200145e#post_558f5be5636872710200145e
"@liamwhite1":/dis/the-time-wasting-thread/post/558f5c5963687251bd000829#post_558f5c5963687251bd000829
Not to ask a stupid question but this has been bothering me: why is it that computer languages for the most part don't have anything to understand complex mathematical symbols?

On the one hand I can understand why getting the relative compliment of two matrix would be difficult to put into a computer language, but on the other hand that would save so much time typing shit out.

Also why is it that they're not programmed to follow the orders of operations for formulas?  If say you're typing out a physics equation on the one hand breaking it down into it's individual components reduces the margin of error, but on the other hand typing it out as one equation would make it simpler if you just need a rough number.

Tl:dr; why don't computer languages accept complex mathematics?
